name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: Feminist protests in Mexico City tonight. Activists are demanding an end to violence against women — and that the country’s ruling party drop its support for a gubernatorial candidate accused by multiple women of rape.  https://t.co/Ih4iR5aUlO

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: We talk a lot about Mexico's "disappeared," the 80,000 people who have gone missing in the drug war.  But there's a growing realization that many were buried by the government in common graves.  My story w/ @mayaaverbuch about a daunting forensic crisis.   https://t.co/mjQq9Kq16p

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: It's unlikely AMLO will drop Salgado. It's likely that feminist protests will grow.  For many, it comes down to this: @lopezobrador_  was faced with opposing accounts from two political allies.   One said the other had raped her. AMLO stood by the man.   https://t.co/j0fNQUu7N3

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: The growing number of women calling for an end to gender violence in Mexico represents “the one true thorn in AMLO’s side: a singular political movement that he does not seem to understand, cannot control and will be unable to suppress,” @DeniseDresserG wrote in @AmerQuarterly

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: AMLO is pugnacious. After decades in the opposition, it's part of his DNA to reject any criticism as an attack from his political enemies.  But that's a bad look when the critique comes from women complaining of violence. Analysts call Mexico's feminists AMLO's "Achilles heel."

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: For Mexico's increasingly visible feminist movement, the case represents all that is wrong in Mexico, where there is near-impunity in rape cases, and where 11 women are murdered each day.  They have launched street protests around the country in response.   https://t.co/Qlrr4csP8F

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: Another victim told police she was drugged and raped at Salgado's Acapulco home in 2016. Her case went nowhere. This year, the prosecutor in the case told journalists that he was pressured to drop it by the state's governor.  Salgado denies all assault claims.

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: There is nothing that suggests this is a partisan attack.   One of the accusers, Basilia Casteñeda, is a founding member of Morena, AMLO and Salgado's party.  She says she was 17 when Salgado raped her. She only came forward after hearing he had allegedly raped somebody else.

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: Salgado's candidacy has divided Mexico's ruling party. On  one side are female party members who want him replaced.   On the other is AMLO who has dismissed the rape claims as part of a partisan attack. "Enough already!" he recently exclaimed when asked again about the case.

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: Five women have accused Mexican politician Félix Salgado Macedonio of sexual assault.   Yet the country's ruling party just named him their candidate in a major governor's race.   What follows is a short thread on AMLO, feminism and #MeToo in Mexico.   https://t.co/j0fNQUu7N3

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: During the pandemic, every Catholic ritual -- from baptism to confession -- has become an opportunity for contagion.  As his fellow priests started dying en masse, one young Mexican priest asked God: How can we be close to our flock but also protected?   https://t.co/DVPFnXw4oK

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: The pandemic has decimated the Catholic church, which was already struggling to recruit priests.   I wrote about a year in the life of one young Mexican priest, who, after watching five mentors die of Covid-19, hatched a creative plan to save his diocese.   https://t.co/DVPFnXetxc

name: Kate Linthicum

name: Kate Linthicum
tweet: The 15-year-old's mother begged him not to leave Guatemala.   But the boy insisted. He earned $3 a day in the coffee fields and thought if he worked in the US he could buy his mom a house.  The family says he was one of 19 bodies found in Mexico this week   https://t.co/VgeXtBwhns
